==Japanese==
{{ja-kanjitab|alt=彼の}}

===Etymology===
Originally a compound of {{com|ja|sort=あの|あ|tr1=a|pos1=[[distal]] [[pronominal]] marker|の|tr2=no|pos2=genitive particle}}.

===Pronunciation===
{{ja-pron|acc=0}}

===Adnominal===
{{ja-pos|adnominal}}

# ''([[deictically]])'' [[that]] ... over there (far from the speaker and the addressee)
#: {{ja-usex|'''あの'''車は緑です。|'''あの''' くるま は みどり です。|'''That''' car '''over there''' is green.}}
# ''([[anaphorically]])'' [[that]] ... we both know (both the speaker and the addressee know)

====Usage notes====
* As an [[adnominal]], {{lang|ja|あの}} must be followed by a noun or noun phrase.
* あの is also used to refer to things and experiences that both the speaker and the listener have knowledge of. Compare the two following sentences,
*: {{ja-usex|'''あの'''本はやすいですか？|'''あの''' ほん は やすい です か？|Is that book (over there, which you and I can see) cheap?}}
*: {{ja-usex|'''その'''本はやすいですか？|'''その''' ほん は やすい です か？|Is that book (I'm pointing to/near you/of yours) cheap? / Is that book which you (have/saw/were talking about) cheap?}}
* The hiragana spelling ({{m|ja|あの}}) is preferred to the kanji spelling ({{m|ja|彼の}}), which is rarely used.

